issue.title: Project Scope Readme
issue.body:
(After spending a few hours trying to figure out GitHub, this is as far as I got.  So you lucky reader get to see everything in one text file.)

Short Overview:

PiDrive is a replacement instrument cluster and data collection system.  It serves a similar purpose to PiDash (no affiliation), but PiDrive is intended for 1995 and earlier vehicles or vehicles which don't have CANBUS.

Inspiration:

I own a 1986 Chrysler Laser XT with an analog instrument cluster.  Every single gauge and light in the cluster was faulty.  I found the one remaining cluster in the known world, and it was almost entirely broken as well.  Other trim levels of the car had a digital dash, but converting would be very difficult.  In order to pass a safety inspection in my state, I must have at minimum a light to indicate that turn signals are on and a light to indicate that my high beams are on.  That could be done with wire, light bulbs, and a piece of cardboard with magic marker, but I wanted to make it better.  In keeping with the 1980's electronics-heavy theme of the car, I want an advanced digital dash.

Components:

* Vehicle Interface
A Raspberry Pi Pico 2 will connect to vehicle sensors and output a stream of human-readable data via TTY.  (I've written some simple BASIC code to do this, and it simply PRINTs the collected data.)  As a standalone part, this could be useful as a driving data logger when connected to a laptop's USB port.

* GUI
A Raspberry Pi 4 B on an appropriately-sized LCD sits in the vehicle's instrument cluster cavity.  This will display all of the expected vehicle statistics.  As a standalone part, it can read turn signals and lights that are in the vehicle's instrument cluster wire harness, and it could also be made to accept a GPS module to display vehicle speed in lieu of receiving interpreted vehicle speed distance sensor data from the Vehicle Interface.

* Accessories
3D printed models for enclosures
Adapters, sensors, voltage dividers, wire harnesses, or other parts to make it easier to read vehicle data

To Do:

Some sensors will need to be better understood.  Speed Distance sensors, for instance, typically output pulses for the rotation of the output shaft.  However, they range from 0.5v to 14v depending on the sensor.  Fuel level sending units are usually resistors, so what are some baseline readings between empty and full?  Tach is easy; 12v trigger to the coil.  Engine temperature is easy, too.  It's well documented.  Knock sensors are easy.

The Pi Pico needs to be hooked up to the car and driven around to collect data and output it to a laptop, so that we can see the interpreted data it outputs.

The Pi 4 needs to BOOT quickly and begin displaying the critical driving information.  I think a stripped down Linux with X running a simple SDL program will suffice for now.

Future Plans:

Interface the Pi Pico 2 with modern aftermarket sensors, such as wideband, boost, fuel pressure, TPMS, ambient temperature, etc.

Graphical templates to match vehicle aesthetics.

Option for additional LCD + Pi Pico for navigation, info, and entertainment.

Backup Camera

360 Degree Recording

Voice Commands ("Hey Eva, navigate me to the nearest drive-in theater")

Voice Feedback ("A door is a-jar")

Vehicle Security System and/or Tracking

Diagnostic Assistant (detecting and logging knock, heat spikes, boost spikes, VSS mismatch, misfire, low fuel or oil pressure, etc., and providing alerts, possible causes, and resolutions)

issue.title: Bug: IMAP connector skips existing emails during initial sync
issue.body:
## Bug: IMAP connector skips existing emails during initial sync

### Description
The IMAP connector fails to synchronize existing/historical emails when setting up a new ingestion. Only new emails that arrive after the sync process starts are fetched. This results in data loss as all pre-existing emails in the mailbox are never imported.

### Current Behavior
- Set up a new IMAP ingestion for a mailbox containing existing emails
- The connector fetches only new incoming emails
- All emails that existed before the sync started are permanently skipped
- This happens consistently on every fresh ingestion setup (at least with certain IMAP servers)

### Expected Behavior
- Initial sync should fetch ALL emails in the mailbox
- Subsequent syncs should fetch only new emails (incremental sync)
- No emails should be skipped or lost

issue.title: Async support for hooks is broken because of incorrect code in HookMetadataGenerator
issue.body:
Hi,

I updated to the latest TUnit version 0.56.5 and now my async `[Before(Test)]` hooks aren't working properly because they are not being awaited.

I have traced the error to the following line:
https://github.com/thomhurst/TUnit/blob/fcbe27a9019f5f2de6917ae13d6642b2c6a0d533/TUnit.Core.SourceGenerator/Generators/HookMetadataGenerator.cs#L627

It seems to be trying to convert `result` to something that can be awaited but since it is passing in a local `Func<object>` then it will always end up running `syncFunc()` in `AsyncConvert` which isn't the intention.
https://github.com/thomhurst/TUnit/blob/fcbe27a9019f5f2de6917ae13d6642b2c6a0d533/TUnit.Core/AsyncConvert.cs#L65-L69

To be clear, the before hook is being called, but TUnit continues execution without waiting for the async operation to complete so tests end up running before the hook is done running.

comment.body: I've worked around the problem for now by doing blocking waits in my before hooks.
